New findings from Claude Projects review:
Auto-detection compiler boundary needs explicit rules:
The design assumes PistonCore can reliably auto-detect whether a piston compiles to YAML or PyScript. In practice the boundary is fuzzy and edge cases will confuse users when the same logic compiles differently after a small edit. Before writing the compiler define an explicit, testable, ordered list of conditions that force PyScript compilation. The list must be unambiguous — no judgment calls. If any condition on the list is true the piston compiles to PyScript. Otherwise it compiles to YAML. This list becomes part of DESIGN.md and the compiler implements it exactly.
hass --script check_config validates entire config not one file:
Running full HA config validation on every save is slow and potentially disruptive. Reconsider the validation pipeline — options are: run full validation only on deploy not on save, find a targeted single-file validation approach, or accept that YAML validation is deploy-time only and make that clear to users. Internal PistonCore validation (missing triggers, undefined globals etc.) still runs on save — only the HA-side check_config call is affected by this.
Copy AI Prompt feature needs redesign:
The current design says clicking Copy AI Prompt copies only the JSON format spec with no user data. A fresh AI review correctly identified that an AI given only a schema spec will produce generic useless output. The feature needs to include at minimum the role labels defined in the piston being worked on, and ideally a plain English description of the user's mapped devices. Rethink this feature before implementing it — the privacy goal (no entity IDs) is correct but the implementation as described will disappoint users.
Role creation during piston building is undefined:
When a user picks a device in the wizard while building a piston from scratch — does it become a named role or a hard entity reference? This decision is not defined anywhere in the design and it shapes the entire piston data model. Roles exist for sharing — if a user is building a piston just for themselves they may not want or need roles. Options: always create roles automatically with a generated name, always use hard entity references internally and only convert to roles on Snapshot export, or ask the user. This must be decided before the editor data model is designed.
Drag and drop cannot be deferred:
Section 7 defers drag behavior to implementation. This is a blocker — drag and drop behavior affects the document data model, undo/redo, and state management. It must be decided before the editor data model is designed. Add to next session agenda: define drag and drop rules before touching the editor data model.
